#### A way to actually get raw requests sent by curl:

1. run netcat listening; its output is the request: `nc -l 9999 > raw_request.txt`
2. run curl with timeout (in order to not hang), proxying to nc: `timeout 2 curl [http://example.com](http://example.com/) --proxy [http://localhost:9999](http://localhost:9999/)`

`nc -l 9999 > raw_request.txt & timeout 2 curl [http://example.com](http://example.com/) --http1.0 --proxy [http://localhost:9999](http://localhost:9999/)` is a working command (might adjust the timeout tho), replace `curl [http://example.com](http://example.com`)` with a command for a target request to make it working

#### Using netcat to get raw request+response

After getting a raw request from the step earlier simply use something like `netcat [localhost 8080](http://localhost:8080) < raw_request.txt`, it requires the nginx hostname and the port. The goal of this task is to completely automate this and generate a few test cases on common setups. Prepare some nginx configs and setups to then send and receive those files, also modifying the nginx directory contents



A good first step is a tiny raw-HTTP test script that talks to NGINX exactly like your future server will.

This avoids browser “helpfulness” and shows the real request/response format.

1) What this script does
opens a TCP connection to NGINX
sends a raw HTTP request
prints the full response
lets you compare:
	status line
	headers
	body
	error pages
	redirects
This is useful because your webserv project must match HTTP behavior closely.

2) Minimal test script
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import socket
import sys

def send_request(host, port, request_text):
    s = socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
    s.connect((host, port))
    s.sendall(request_text.encode())

    response = b""
    while True:
        chunk = s.recv(4096)
        if not chunk:
            break
        response += chunk

    s.close()
    return response.decode("utf-8", errors="replace")

def main():
    host = "127.0.0.1"
    port = 8080

    if len(sys.argv) >= 2:
        port = int(sys.argv[1])

    request = (
        "GET / HTTP/1.1\r\n"
        f"Host: {host}:{port}\r\n"
        "Connection: close\r\n"
        "\r\n"
    )

    response = send_request(host, port, request)
    print("=== REQUEST ===")
    print(request)
    print("=== RESPONSE ===")
    print(response)

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()

3) Step-by-step explanation
socket.socket(socket.AF_INET, socket.SOCK_STREAM)
Creates a TCP socket.

AF_INET means IPv4
SOCK_STREAM means TCP, not UDP
HTTP over NGINX uses TCP.

s.connect((host, port))
Connects to the server at 127.0.0.1:8080.

This is the same idea your future client connections will use.

s.sendall(request_text.encode())
Sends the full HTTP request.

The request is plain text:

request line: GET / HTTP/1.1
headers: Host, Connection
empty line ends headers
The blank line is important. Without it, HTTP parsing is incomplete.

while True: chunk = s.recv(4096)
Reads the response until the server closes the connection.

This is simple and works well for a first test.

Since we send Connection: close, NGINX will usually close after the response, so this loop finishes.

errors="replace"
If the response contains bytes that are not valid UTF-8, the script does not crash.

It replaces them with placeholder characters.

